
<h2>11 22, 1963</h2>""<p>Lyndon Baines Johnson is sworn in as the thirty-sixth President of the United States following the assassination of John F. Kennedy.</p>
<h2>11 27, 1963</h2>""<p>Johnson addresses a joint session of Congress calling on legislators to fulfill Kennedy's legacy and pass civil rights and tax legislation. </p>
<h2>11 29, 1963</h2>""<p>Johnson creates a special commission chaired by Chief Justice Earl Warren to investigate the Kennedy assassination. </p>
<h2>1 23, 1964</h2>""<p>The Twenty-Fourth Amendment to the Constitution is ratified, abolishing poll taxes. </p>
<h2>2 7, 1964</h2>""<p>The Beatles arrive in New York for their first U.S. tour. </p>
<h2>3 14, 1964</h2>""<p>Jack Ruby is convicted of the murder of Lee Harvey Oswald and sentenced to death. </p>
<h2>5 22, 1964</h2>""<p>In a speech at the University of Michigan, Johnson announces his intention to create a Great Society by extending American prosperity to all its citizens. </p>
<h2>7 2, 1964</h2>""<p>Johnson signs The Civil Rights Act of 1964. </p>
<h2>7 15, 1964</h2>""<p>Sen. Barry Goldwater (R-AZ) receives the Republican nomination for President. </p>
<h2>7 19, 1964</h2>""<p>Governor George Wallace of Alabama drops out of the presidential race despite strong showings in several Democratic primaries. </p>
<h2>8 4, 1964</h2>""<p>Three civil rights workers are found dead in Mississippi. James Chaney, Andrew Goodman, and Michael Schwerner were all participating in the Mississippi Freedom Summer. </p>
<h2>8 7, 1964</h2>""<p>Congress passes the Gulf of Tonkin Resolution giving the President power to pursue military action in Vietnam. </p>
<h2>8 26, 1964</h2>""<p>Johnson receives the Democratic nomination for President. Senator Hubert H. Humphrey (D-MN) is nominated as the vice-presidential candidate. </p>
<h2>8 30, 1964</h2>""<p>Johnson signs the Economic Opportunity Act, creating the Office of Economic Opportunity and beginning the War on Poverty. </p>
<h2>9 27, 1964</h2>""<p>The Warren Commission releases its report, rejecting the notion that Kennedy was assassinated as part of a conspiracy. </p>
<h2>10 14, 1964</h2>""<p>Martin Luther King Jr. is awarded the Nobel Peace Prize. </p>
<h2>10 15, 1964</h2>""<p>Nikita Khrushchev is forced to resign as leader of the Soviet Union and is replaced by Leonid Brezhnev. </p>
<h2>11 3, 1964</h2>""<p>Lyndon B. Johnson is elected President of the United States. </p>
<h2>1 20, 1965</h2>""<p>Johnson is inaugurated President of the United States. </p>
<h2>2 9, 1965</h2>""<p>Nine American soldiers are killed in an attack on U.S. barracks in Pleiku, Vietnam. Johnson begins the bombing of North Vietnam. </p>
<h2>2 21, 1965</h2>""<p>Malcolm X is assassinated by other black Muslims in New York City. </p>
<h2>3 15, 1965</h2>""<p>Johnson calls for voting rights legislation. </p>
<h2>3 21, 1965</h2>""<p>Martin Luther King Jr. leads a march from Selma to Montgomery, Alabama. </p>
<h2>4 11, 1965</h2>""<p>Johnson signs the Elementary and Secondary Education Act. </p>
<h2>4 28, 1965</h2>""<p>Johnson sends U.S. marines to the Dominican Republic to protect U.S. citizens after a military coup. </p>
<h2>6 7, 1965</h2>""<p>The U.S. Supreme Court finds a Connecticut law banning the use of contraceptives unconstitutional. </p>
<h2>7 26, 1965</h2>""<p>Martin Luther King Jr. leads a demonstration in Chicago in an attempt to bring the Civil Rights Movement to the North. </p>
<h2>7 28, 1965</h2>""<p>Johnson increases the number of troops sent to Vietnam, indicating his determination to engage in a ground war. </p>
<h2>7 30, 1965</h2>""<p>Johnson signs legislation creating Medicare and Medicaid. </p>
<h2>8 , 1965</h2>""<p>A paper by Daniel Patrick Moynihan, entitled, <i>The Negro Family: The Case For National Action</i>, is released. The conclusions of the "Moynihan Report" create heated controversy. </p>
<h2>8 5, 1965</h2>""<p>Johnson signs the Voting Rights Act into law. </p>
<h2>8 11-16, 1965</h2>""<p>The Watts Riots break out in Los Angeles. </p>
<h2>2 21, 1966</h2>""<p>Fearing that American involvement in Vietnam will draw France into a world war, French president Charles de Gaulle announces that France will withdraw from NATO. </p>
<h2>3 7, 1966</h2>""<p>The U.S. Supreme Court unanimously upholds the Voting Rights Act of 1965. </p>
<h2>6 1-2, 1966</h2>""<p>The White House Conference on Civil Rights urges Congress to pass further civil rights legislation. </p>
<h2>6 6, 1966</h2>""<p>James Meredith is shot in a March from Memphis, Tennessee, to Jackson, Mississippi; civil rights leaders organize to complete his march. During this demonstration, Stokely Carmichael makes a statement in support of "black power." </p>
<h2>6 13, 1966</h2>""<p>In <i>Miranda v. Arizona</i>, the U.S. Supreme Court rules that the constitutional provision against self-incrimination applies to police interrogations. </p>
<h2>10 , 1966</h2>""<p>Huey P. Newton and Bobby Seale found the Black Panther Party in Oakland, California. </p>
<h2>1 27, 1967</h2>""<p>A launch pad fire during tests for the Apollo program kills three astronauts. </p>
<h2>2 10, 1967</h2>""<p>The Twenty-Fifth Amendment to the Constitution is ratified, providing rules of succession upon the death or incapacitation of the President, and enabling the President to appoint a new vice-president in the case of a vacancy. </p>
<h2>6 5, 1967</h2>""<p>The Six Day War breaks out between Israel and several Arab nations. </p>
<h2>6 14, 1967</h2>""<p>Johnson appoints Thurgood Marshall to the Supreme Court. </p>
<h2>7 13, 1967</h2>""<p>Riots break out in Newark, New Jersey.</p>
<h2>7 23, 1967</h2>""<p>Riots spread across the city of Detroit, Michigan. </p>
	
<h2>10 21, 1967</h2>""<p>Anti-war demonstrators March to the Pentagon in an attempt to shut it down. </p>
<h2>1 22, 1968</h2>""<p>North Korean forces capture the <i>U.S.S. Pueblo</i>. </p>
<h2>1 30, 1968</h2>""<p>North Vietnamese troops surprise South Vietnamese and American troops by attacking during the Tet holiday. While the Tet Offensive is not a military loss for the United States, it leads to a loss of confidence in the Johnson administration's prosecution of the war. </p>
<h2>2 8, 1968</h2>""<p>George Wallace enters the presidential race as an independent. </p>
<h2>3 12, 1968</h2>""<p>Johnson wins the New Hampshire Democratic primary, but anti-war candidate Eugene McCarthy comes in a close second with 42 percent of the vote. </p>
<h2>3 16, 1968</h2>""<p>U.S. forces in Vietnam commit massacre in the hamlet of My Lai; hundreds of unarmed men, women, and children are killed. News of the event would not reach the public until November 1969. </p>
<h2>3 16, 1968</h2>""<p>Robert Kennedy enters the race for the Democratic nomination for President. </p>
<h2>3 31, 1968</h2>""<p>Johnson announces a partial bombing halt and his unwillingness to seek reelection to the presidency. </p>
<h2>4 4, 1968</h2>""<p>Martin Luther King Jr. is assassinated in Memphis, Tennessee. </p>
<h2>4 23, 1968</h2>""<p>Students at Columbia University take over several buildings on campus. </p>
<h2>4 29, 1968</h2>""<p>Ralph Abernathy of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference (SCLC) begins the Poor People's Campaign in Washington, D.C.</p>
<h2>5 13, 1968</h2>""<p>The United States and North Vietnam begin peace talks in Paris. </p>
<h2>6 5, 1968</h2>""<p>Senator Robert Kennedy is assassinated after winning the Democratic primary in California. </p>
<h2>8 20-21, 1968</h2>""<p>The Soviet Union invades Czechoslovakia to end the movement toward greater freedom and independence. </p>
<h2>8 25-29, 1968</h2>""<p>Hubert H. Humphrey is nominated in Chicago as the Democratic candidate for President.  Demonstrators and police clash in violent confrontations. </p>
<h2>11 5, 1968</h2>""<p>Richard M. Nixon is elected President of the United States, and Spiro Agnew is elected vice-president. </p>
<h2>11 12, 1968</h2>""<p>Leonid Brezhnev announces that the Soviet Union has the right to intervene anywhere in its sphere of influence. This "Brezhnev Doctrine" becomes central to Soviet foreign policy. </p>
